post_text:
This was not the first day that we were hoping for!

FPS has cancelled classes for the remainder of the day on Tuesday, 9/8/2020 in order to focus on DORA Access Issues. Elementary conferences will continue as previously planned. We will provide an update about the status of tomorrow's classes by 6pm on Tuesday, 9/8/2020.

Thank you for your patience and understanding.

---
Update 12:35pm

In preparation for logging in to classes tomorrow, please take the following steps to update your computer’s software prior to the start of school

1. Restart your district device
2. Log on to the FPS computer using your username and password
3. Make sure that you are connected to the internet
4. Expect to see a maintenance message” after a short period of time. If you do not see a maintenance message within ten minutes, please restart your FPS computer again.
5. The maintenance process will restart your computer automatically when it has completed the updates
6. Log on to the computer using your username and password
7. Go to dora.fpschools.org to access remote learning tools

With participation from various county behavioral health clinicians and school professionals.

post_text:
This afternoon, Governor Inslee ordered the closure of all schools in King, Pierce and Snohomish counties. Tomorrow, March 13 will be the last day of school until Monday, April 27.

We understand that this plan will create hardship for many families, and we appreciate your patience and cooperation.

There are many unknowns at this point, but we will do our best to offer updates via social media, email, voicemail and the district website at www.fpschools.org.

Last week, Franklin Pierce Schools welcomed our newest administrator, Miss Franklin to Brookdale Elementary! Miss Franklin, a first grader, was selected as Principal for the Day for generating the most sales in the Brookdale PTA fundraiser. She had a busy schedule signing a contract with the HR Department, meeting with the Superintendent and Deputy Superintendent to discuss her views on education, supervising lunch and recess, and visiting teachers throughout her school.

Well done Miss Franklin!

Thank you for your care and concern as we do our best to make our schools safe and supportive learning environments.

post_text: Many families in the Franklin Pierce Schools community may be impacted by zoning changes in our area. Please consider attending this important open house to make your voice heard.
shared_text:
Pierce County Planning & Public Works
April 3, 2019 at 10:07 AM ·

Join us April 13 for an open house about proposed updates to the Frederickson, Mid-County, Parkland-Spanaway-Midland and South Hill Community Plans.

Community plans provide direction on how growth and development will be handled. The plans address topics such as zoning, transportation, the look and feel of the community, and access to services and amenities.

Stop by the Pierce County Skills Center at 16117 Canyon Road E in Puyallup any time between 10 a.m. and 3 p.m. to view displays and talk to staff. Short presentations will be made at 10 a.m., noon and 2 p.m. Can’t make it? An online version of the open house is available at www.piercecountywa.gov/cpupdate.

post_text:
Due to the condition of roads throughout the district, Franklin Pierce Schools will operate with the following schedule on Wednesday, 2/13:

-All schools will start 2 hours late.
-All schools will dismiss at the regular time (the scheduled 90-minute early release is canceled).
-There will be no out-of-district transportation.
-There will be no Hewins ELC preschool programs.
-There will be no breakfast service.
-There will be no activities bus.

District employees will continue to monitor the roads overnight and notify students, staff and families of changes as soon as possible.

This message pertains to Franklin Pierce High School families whose households have been impacted by the goverment shutdown.

For more information, please visit https://goo.gl/oEzzCe.
shared_text:
Franklin Pierce High School
January 18, 2019 at 9:37 AM ·

HOUSEHOLDS AFFECTED BY THE GOVERNMENT SHUTDOWN:

Households of furloughed employees affected by the government shutdown may be temporary eligible for free or reduced-price meal benefits. While free and reduced-price meal eligibility is intended to reflect actual annual income, applications may reflect the current households situation. This unique situation does not necessarily provide households with information on the duration of the furlough or the ultimate impact on the household income.

Federally furloughed households approved for meal benefits will need to terminate or update their free/reduced-price status once the economic hardship is remedied due to returning to work and/or restoration of pay for the furlough period.

If you have any questions regarding this unique situation, please contact the Nutrition Services office at 253-298-4618.

PSA: If you are in the mood for pizza, swing by Farrelli's Pizza - Parkland and be sure to buy some breadsticks. 10% of the proceeds will go toward purchasing school supplies for students throughout the school year!
shared_text:
United Way of Pierce County
September 13, 2018 at 3:05 PM ·

We are so proud to partner with WestRock on a recent school supply drive for Franklin Pierce School District. Their employees collected school supplies and delivered them in boxes from a local, Tacoma donut store. (The paper that WestRock makes is used on the donut store box.) In addition to helping more kids start the school year right, they're one of our Premier Partners sponsors! WestRock indeed Rocks! Pictured:Debbie Whitt, Lore Smith, Tiffany Kuluwaimaka with United Way's Missy Zenczak.

Due to unanticipated setbacks in the parking lot project, the Dr. Frank Hewins Early Learning Center will begin classes on Monday, September 17. Staff have been communicating with impacted families. If you have questions about your child's enrollment or start date at the ELC, please call (253)298-4675.

Fun Fact: The new paved parking lot will have over 258,000 gallons of water storage under it to prevent flooding after a major rain event!

post_text: Tonight, members of the community gathered to dream about the future of the Farm at Franklin Pierce. In conjunction with our partners from Pierce Conservation District/Harvest Pierce County, we are looking to develop a STEM facility that will serve students and community farmers. The Farm at Franklin Pierce generates healthy produce for summer lunches, local food banks and a weekly farmers market held at Keithley. Stay tuned as we seek to gather additional input over the next few months!

This month marks the beginning of Mr. Lance Goodpaster’s new role as the superintendent of Franklin Pierce Schools. Superintendent Goodpaster has worked closely with the Franklin Pierce Board of Directors and recently retired Superintendent, Dr. Frank Hewins over the past year to ensure a seamless transition.

Thank you Dr. Hewins for your years of service and we look forward to Superintendent Goodpaster’s leadership in the next chapter of Franklin Pierce Schools.

To learn more about the transition, visit: www.fpschools.org.

post_text: Last night, Christensen Elementary hosted the annual Battle of the Books Contest. This year's competition featured students from six district elementary schools. Students prepared for the event by reading 20 books and tested their comprehension through a series of "battles" with other teams. Brookdale Elementary took home the 2018 prize after a nail-biting finish with Collins Elementary. Congratulations to all of the students, parents and staff that participated!

post_text: Students at Central Avenue Elementary proudly showed off their science experiments at the school’s annual STEM Night. 5th grader Jacob Jackson designed and built a mechanical hand with straws and draw strings to test the dexterity comparisons between human hands and mechanical hands. 5th grader Amber Frickel studied the differences of bacteria types and levels found in human mouths (her dad’s and baby sister’s) and Jack, her family’s pet dog. These were among dozens of other fantastic science experiments on display! We have some future scientists in our midst!

On Saturday, April 21st, a group of school staff will be hosting the 7th annual Hoops for Hope, a 3-on-3 charity basketball tournament. The event is in honor of Pamela Raynor, a Franklin Pierce School District teacher, Pacific Lutheran University alumnus, and former Puyallup basketball player who lost her own battle with cancer. Raynor started Hoops for Hope.

The event will be held at Franklin Pierce High School (11002 18th Avenue East). There is a $60 registration fee per team of three players. All proceeds will be donated to the American Cancer Society.

Click the link below for more information and the registration form.

post_text: Students in Mr. Stugelmeyer's Outdoor Living elective class at Keithley Middle School learned about water safety by Lee Warnaca of the Tacoma Maritime Institute. The students learned about cold water survival, knot tying, safety equipment, and more. Update: The suspect was arrested yesterday. School will operate normally today (Tuesday), January 9.

Original Post from January 8: As you are aware, there was a tragic incident early this morning in Frederickson that resulted in the death of a Pierce County Sheriff’s Department deputy. Our hearts go out to the family of the officer involved, as well as the entire Pierce County Sheriff’s Department for their dedication and service to the community. Even though this incident occurred outside the borders of Franklin Pierce School District, we took extra precautionary measures by operating all schools in a modified lockdown status, which includes locked doors and heightened supervision during transition periods. This is merely to provide additional layers of safety for students and staff.

post_text:
Congratulations to Dr. Hewins, who was named the 2018 Superintendent of the Year by the Washington Association of School Administrators (WASA)!

This award is designed to recognize the outstanding leadership of active, front-line superintendents and pay tribute to those who lead our public schools.

As the state’s Superintendent of the Year, Dr. Hewins also will serve as a candidate for the 2018 American Association of School Administrators’ National Superintendent of the Year award. The national award will be announced in February at the AASA National Conference on Education in Nashville, TN.

Congratulations, Dr. Hewins, and thank you for your exceptional leadership!

Congratulations to Dr. Hewins, who was named the 2018 Superintendent of the Year by the Washington Association of School Administrators (WASA)!

This award is designed to recognize the outstanding leadership of active, front-line superintendents and pay tribute to those who lead our public schools.

As the state’s Superintendent of the Year, Dr. Hewins also will serve as a candidate for the 2018 American Association of School Administrators’ National Superintendent of the Year award. The national award will be announced in February at the AASA National Conference on Education in Nashville, TN.

Congratulations, Dr. Hewins, and thank you for your exceptional leadership!

2017 Washington Patriot Cross Country Season Summary

This year’s cross country team at Washington High School carried on the program’s tradition of excellence, earning the Distinguished Academic Award from the Washington Interscholastic Activities Association (WIAA) for the 11th consecutive year.

Here are some highlights from this year’s season:
- For league honors, the boys’ team was given the
Sportsmanship Award for the 6th time in the last 8 years.
- Over the course of the season, the girls’ team beat 52 other
teams and the boys’ team beat 77 other teams.
- In the Division, the girls’ team placed 4th and the boys’ team
placed 3rd.
- At the League Meet, the girls’ team placed 10th and the boys’
team placed 3rd.
- At the District Meet, the girls’ team placed 13th and the boys’
team placed 6th.
- 18 athletes qualified for the District Meet.
- 3 athletes qualified for the State Meet.

Way to go!

In the VIEWS newsletter that was recently mailed, there was an article on page 5 that explained when vehicles need to stop for a school bus. The article was correct, but the infographic that accompanied it was not.

As a reminder, you must always stop if you are traveling in the same direction as the school bus. On a two-lane road, traffic in both directions needs to stop. If there are three or more lanes, or a divided roadway, you are not required to stop if you’re traveling in the opposite direction of the bus. Please keep in mind, that even if you are not required to stop, you need to proceed with caution.

A correction will be published in the next edition of the newsletter. We apologize for this error.

Last week, students from Keithley Middle School got to taste fresh, locally grown produce harvested from the district farm on 96th Street and Waller Road. Students tasted whole carrots, green pepper slices, peas, and squash slices.

Students from the district have field trips to the farm throughout the school year to learn about farming and assist with the different stages of vegetable production. The farm also benefits greatly from a partnership with Harvest Pierce County's Veggie Co-op which coordinates community volunteers who assist in the farm's operation.

Fresh produce from the farm will be served in school meals around the district while there is still produce to harvest.

post_text: Starting Monday, October 2, all parents, students in grades 5 through 12, and all district employees will have an opportunity to participate in a new survey that will help school officials assess climate and culture within schools and the district. Parents will have an opportunity to take the survey at their child’s school during conference week (October 2-5) in conjunction with conferences. Students in grades 5 through 12 and all district employees will have an opportunity to take the survey at school between October 2 and October 13. The survey will take the place of the Student Led Conference (SLC) surveys that parents have historically taken during conference week.

District officials were made aware of an anonymous and vague threatening message via social media earlier today. The message does not specify any school or school district. District officials have been working with our School Resource Officers, who are Pierce County Sheriff’s Deputies, to attempt to determine the source of this message. We currently don’t know if the message was created by someone within or outside the Franklin Pierce community, nor do we know for whom the message was intended.

All school staff throughout the district will exercise higher-than-usual awareness. All schools are prepared to take extra safety precautions as needed.

Always remember: If you see or hear something, say something…even if you think it may not be serious. We take all alleged threats seriously. The safety of our students and staff is always our first priority.

post_text:
September marks “Attendance Awareness Month.”

The goal of the month is to raise awareness around the importance of students attending school daily and how it connects to academic achievement.

According to numerous studies, missing several days of school significantly reduces the likelihood that students will succeed academically and even graduate from high school.

With attendance being a crucial factor in keeping kids on the right path to graduation, Attendance Works, has substantial information on attendance and the impact on student achievement.

Visit www.AttendanceWorks.org for more information on the importance of regular and on-time attendance.

post_text: "Previously deemed a 'dropout factory,' [Washington High] made a campuswide shift in 2006 to focus on freshmen. That eventually helped boost its on-time graduation rate from 61 percent in 2009 to 87 percent last year."
shared_text:
SEATTLETIMES.COM
How high schools break up the ‘ninth-grade bottleneck’ to help students graduate on time

The Seattle Times
September 2, 2017 at 8:34 AM ·

Turns out, freshman year of high school is an indicator of a lot of things – including whether or not you’ll graduate. When two schools in Tacoma and Seattle figured this out, they buckled down on first-year student performance. It’s paying off: at West Seattle High School last year, 92 percent of freshmen advanced to 10th grade on time.
